cript culture and talismanic use introduces the concept of biblical mediation, a new way to explore Scriptures and society. It challenges the lay-clerical divide by demonstrating that biblical exegesis was presented to the laity in non-textual means, while the ‘naked text’ of the Bible remained elusive even for the educated clergy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aMediationxReligious aspectsxChristianityxHistoryyTo 1500. 4aMedieval Studies 2020. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh  aAdvent Sunday sermons.  aBible.  aLate Antiquity.  aPalm Sunday.  abiblical manuscripts.  abiblical narrative.  adivine authority.  aliturgical spectacles.  amaterial culture.  amedieval England.  amedieval Masses.  aoath rituals.  apreaching techniques.  atalisman.1 aPoleg, Eyal, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagez978311128363040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152611053440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526110534423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526110534/original  a978-3-11-128363-0  Manchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagec1986d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles